Read in data

Here, we assume that the data is stored in the same directory as this script.

# set your working directory - change this to wherever you saved this script and the data file(s)
wd <- "./"

# read in data in edge list form
edgelist_data <- read.csv(paste0(wd,"social_network_edgelist.csv"))

Make and view the network

# make the graph object
g <- graph_from_data_frame(edgelist_data, directed=FALSE)
g
## IGRAPH cad4c7b UNW- 10 16 -- 
## + attr: name (v/c), weight (e/n)
## + edges from cad4c7b (vertex names):
##  [1] Alice  --Bob     Alice  --Dave    Alice  --Eve     Judy   --Faythe 
##  [5] Alice  --Grace   Alice  --Heidi   Alice  --Ivan    Bob    --Charlie
##  [9] Bob    --Eve     Charlie--Eve     Grace  --Heidi   Grace  --Ivan   
## [13] Judy   --Grace   Heidi  --Ivan    Judy   --Heidi   Judy   --Ivan
# plot the graph
plot(g, main="Friendship Network")

# Get the adjacency matrix
get.adjacency(g, sparse=FALSE)

EXERCISE: Make a directed graph and plot it.

Notice that when we created the graph object, we set the “directed” argument to False. To create a directed graph (i.e., one where Alice might like Bob but Bob might not like Alice), change that argument to True.

# make a directed graph object and plot it here

Vertices/Nodes

# get the vertices/nodes/people
V(g)
## + 10/10 vertices, named, from cad4c7b:
##  [1] Alice   Judy    Bob     Charlie Grace   Heidi   Ivan    Dave    Eve    
## [10] Faythe
# get number of vertices (i.e., number of people in the network)
n_vertices <- length(V(g))
n_vertices
## [1] 10

Get/Set node attributes

Attributes that are stored in the graph object

# get the names of the people/nodes/vertices
V(g)$name
##  [1] "Alice"   "Judy"    "Bob"     "Charlie" "Grace"   "Heidi"   "Ivan"   
##  [8] "Dave"    "Eve"     "Faythe"

Add attributes

# add age to the graph object
ages <- c(19, 20, 21, 22, 25, 30, 18, 19, 33, 28)
V(g)$age <- ages
print(V(g)$age)
##  [1] 19 20 21 22 25 30 18 19 33 28

Change plot to reflect age

# "size" is a special attribute that plot() knows, so you can set it equal to any 
# attribute to visualize that attribute in the plot
V(g)$size <- V(g)$age
# plot again
plot(g)

Calculate node-level social network measures

Degree

Degree is the number of edges a node has

# get the number of friends each person has (i.e., degree)
degree(g)
##   Alice    Judy     Bob Charlie   Grace   Heidi    Ivan    Dave     Eve  Faythe 
##       6       4       3       2       4       4       4       1       3       1
hist(degree(g))

# change the size of the vertex based on that vertex's degree
V(g)$size <- degree(g)*2 + 10
plot(g)

In a directed graph, there are two types of degree: in-degree (the number of ties pointing into a node)

degree(g, mode="in")
##   Alice    Judy     Bob Charlie   Grace   Heidi    Ivan    Dave     Eve  Faythe 
##       6       4       3       2       4       4       4       1       3       1

out-degree (the number of ties pointing out of a node)

degree(g, mode="out")
##   Alice    Judy     Bob Charlie   Grace   Heidi    Ivan    Dave     Eve  Faythe 
##       6       4       3       2       4       4       4       1       3       1

Strength

Strength is the sum of the weighted edges connected to a node

strength(g)

##       Eve    Faythe 
## 4.8237170 1.4347515

evc <- eigen_centrality(g)$vector

V(g)$size <- evc*20+10
plot(g)

Brokerage

Betweenness is the extent to which a node sits on the shortest path between two other nodes. In other words, how often do you have to go through that node to reach other nodes?

betweenness(g)
##   Alice    Judy     Bob Charlie   Grace   Heidi    Ivan    Dave     Eve  Faythe 
##      23      21       7       0       0       0      20       0       0       0

Constraint is an inverse measure of brokerage. It reflects the extent to which a node is constrained to its local area.

constraint(g)
##     Alice      Judy       Bob   Charlie     Grace     Heidi      Ivan      Dave 
## 0.4041695 0.4782960 0.8392543 1.0034147 0.6087235 0.6549479 0.8492998 1.0000000 
##       Eve    Faythe 
## 0.6358031 1.0000000

Get edge attributes

Plot graph based on attributes

# make ties in plot thicker based on how strong (either positive or negative) their relationship is
E(g)$width <- abs(E(g)$weight)*5
# plot with weight
plot(g)

# add color attribute to each edge
for (edge in E(g)) {
  # get edge id
  print(edge)
  # get edge weight
  edge_weight <- E(g)[edge]$weight
  # determine if edge was positive or negative
  # if positive, make the edge green
  # if negative, make the edge red
  if (edge_weight >= 1) {
    edge_color <- "blue"
  } else {
    edge_color <- "darkred"
  }
  E(g)[edge]$color <- edge_color
}
